Photo by National Park Geek® in Arches National Park with @travisdamick, @archesnps, and @cnhamoab. May be an image of monument, nature and sky.

node.text:
Dreamy nights. 
••••••
Thanks to Travis  @travisdamick for the Arches magic. 
•
Under the Arch Sky

There’s nothing like capturing a scene like this in a single shot.  Most often I find myself using various techniques to assist with the noise that is brought about by using a high ISO at night. From stacking multiple shots of the same scene to using a tracking device to follow the stars, there is always a way to get more detail out of night shots like this. But with the power of cameras these days there are still those times where the single frame comes out better than I could have imagined.  This was one of those times. 

@sonyalpha a7Riv
20mm f/1.8
10 seconds 
ISO 8000

node.text:
Canyonlands delights the soul. 
——
Thanks to Chris @photographyinfocus for the beautiful views. 
•
The Smoke from the wildfires out west have made it all the way to the east coast. I know it’s very noticeable here in Indiana. 

When I was in Utah just outside of Moab, the smoke  at sunrise in Canyonlands National Park were already noticeable and thick there. I know it goes without saying but always try to do your part to prevent Forrest fires 🐻 

Never let the elements deter you from capturing your shot 📸

node.text:
Reflect on the beauty of Mother Nature and life itself. 
••••
Thanks to our friend Patrick @cliftonwanders for sharing the inspiration of the Yosemite. 
•
A different picture of the same picture I have posted 100 times. Yosemite National Park in May and June takes the cake for me. 
.
Not many people realize that the waterfalls at Yosemite begin to taper in July. They rely on the snowpack in the high country. Water is not only a source of life, it’s a source of action and change. Even in times of drought, regardless of the amount of snowpack, there is always going to be pretty good flow of water in the spring. The melting snow has to go somewhere.
.
Our calls to action for climate change not only affect the global scale, they affect small things like waterfalls and wildflower blooms. As California slowly goes through desertification, who knows the future and shape of places in the high country like Yosemite. If we want to continue to enjoy quality of life, we need to make changes.
.
Yosemite, Ahwahnee, ancestral lands of the Ahwahneechee and Miwok. 
.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Park Geek® in Glacier National Park with @christinaadelephoto, @glaciernps, and @glacierconservancy. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
Spend the weekend with some friends. 
••••
Thanks to our friend Christina  @christinaadelephoto for sharing the Glacier fun and Happy World Ranger Day to you. 
•
Just realizing it’s been almost two months since I have done a post on here. Oops. Summer is fleeting and I have been out enjoying every minute of our extra long days out here. Since May 23rd, we have had a constant stream of friends and family staying with us -many of them whose first time it was to Glacier. So many sweet memories made in the past couple months and I wouldn’t trade it for anything. However, I will say that having our home to ourselves for the first time lately the past two nights has been extra sweet as well.

I realize it’s almost time to share July’s numbers, but I missed sharing the amount of wildlife we spotted in June so here they are: 60 deer, 41 bighorn sheep, 15 grizzly bears, 15 moose, 15 mountain goats, 12 ospreys, 10 turkeys, 6 snowshoe hares, 5 bald eagles, 4 elk, 3 black bears, 2 foxes, 1 beaver, 1 fisher.

Hope your summer so far has been as full of precious memories as mine has been!
——-
